segments.text: a lot of important people.
I was a little apprehensive about serving in things like Norwegian sardines, and they were very popular, and those mussels on a half shell, and they're very popular again.
They just seemed to, I guess that they were so seldom
anywhere until it was just a novelty of some kind.
But they'd take them and eat them.
And I was always amazed at that.
We started at our buffets, by the way.
We would have a lot of fruits and desserts types that they could pick up and take on over to the game if they wanted to.
And of course sometimes they would, not very much.
But I really

I remember the time that we started dipping the fruits in the hot chocolate, which was old hat to a lot of people, but there seemed to be a certain group, too, that really thought that was something special and appreciated the strawberries and some of the dried fruits like apricots were very good dipped in chocolate.
Well, it was always, if you could think of something extra to do, like Dick Cutchish and his method of serving, and you recall him.
He had a method of putting a plate together.
He always used romaine leaves underneath the entrees, and he could make any plate attractive to him.
And I always told him, I said, Dick, you can touch a plate and make it look better.
And that was almost true, almost true.
And then he'd work hours late at night at serving the biggest elaborate, elaborate banquet you could think of.
Go home and eat a peanut butter and jelly sandwich.
Now, in the facilities here, how long could y'all keep fresh lettuce, for example, before it was served?
How many days?
Oh, well, of course, you get it in the head and you cut it, and you'd probably, if you didn't serve it one day, sometimes it'd be good the next.
Probably you wouldn't keep it beyond the second day.
All right, if you haven't broken up the head, how long can it be?
Oh, well, that's about a week.
A week?
Nothing like that.
All right, then fresh beef or pork or chicken that hasn't been frozen, how long can it be kept in the cold storage?
Well, uh, and chill stove.
Well, that's served, that's a week or two easily.
So then there was, there were fresh vegetables, fruits, and meat arriving daily or weekly?
No, no, no.
We didn't use much fresh beef.
We used, uh, we used a lot of the, sometimes the steaks would be.
But most of it came in frozen.
Okay.
Most all the meats.
And it would once per week or per month or what?
Well, that depended on how fast we were using it, but we'd try to get enough to last maybe a month when we bought something, unless it was a very special item.
There were very, very few times we would have something that was just for that one occasion, but it was sometimes that way.
It would be one time, but mostly it was...

something we could hold because you got good enough storage you can keep most anything that's not a fresh product now a carload of beef normally would come from where geographically kansas city omaha colorado okay midwest one of those places the plains okay uh did you ever have any difficulty i'm going to use the word politically
that we were not buying enough from a certain part of the country and we were buying too much from some other part?
Did anybody ever complain?
No, but we had a very closely associated problem.
We used to buy canned beef that was packed in South America.
Ah, okay.
Under our people's jurisdiction, Swift and Company and Armour, and the Beef Growers Association found out about that.
Went to the state and had the law changed so that we couldn't do that anymore.
That was one of the finest beef you've ever seen.
No fat, tender, firmly packed, and we had to quit using it.
Was that law in effect when you retired?
Yes, yes.
As a matter of fact, it had been a number of years before I retired that law went into effect.
Any restrictions on canned goods and their origins, national origin?
Not national origin.
We never would have considered buying anything canned other than packed within the United States.
That all has to be under USDA.
Now what are some points that I haven't written down that I haven't thought of that you must have?
Well, one of the interesting points
is that the opinion of people always thought that we got all our food from the campus, A&M Farms.
And the only product we got from A&M consistently was milk.
And the funny thing happened there, my old friend O.D.
Butler was in charge of the dairy, among other things.
When I came here, I found that I could take bids out of Dallas and have it delivered to me cheaper
into the dining hall, then he would set it on the back dock.
So I started taking bids for milk.
Well, the first thing he heard about it, he had a call from Oak Farms in Dallas that wanted to know how much he wanted to sell the dairy for.
Asked him why.
He said, well, you must be selling it because they didn't buy their milk elsewhere.
So I used to tell the joke that O.D.
walked over on his knees
to talk about it.
I didn't know he was using those funds to support his dairy.
I thought it was an easy sale anywhere that he was just selling us a sort of flavor.
Well, he said, no, he said, it's really important.
He said, don't want to lose that business.
I said, well, you know, you're hiring everybody.
So he explained then the southern milk shed and the northern milk shed.
I said, well, that doesn't matter a hoot to me.
I said, I bought milk.
I was in the military and we furnished milk from where we got it the cheapest.
We have to do that.
We got a dollar and a half a day per person for three meals a day.
So he said, well, you know, I've always been for food service.
I want to do whatever I can for you.
And I said, well, see what you can do.
So he lowered, he figured the price down for us.
And we were always good friends, but it couldn't have gone the other way because
I was totally innocent about the fact that he was depending on that.

Another thing is, I guess you know this story, it was in a, or may not, a lot of people don't know, it was in this book on the moms, it was a book, Moms, Aggies, Moms, and Apple Pies, about the $40,000 pie.
Well, that's the way we got Duncan Hall, my friend E.H. Schmidt.
I learned this story and got him together with the author of this book and got it printed.
And he was the head baker here, and Roosevelt came here in the late 1930s.
And so he baked him an orange chiffon pie, probably the original orange chiffon out of natural ingredients, nothing...
This orange juice and all the things that go with orange chiffon pie.
And President Roosevelt liked this pie real well.
So our physical plant went over and built a refrigerator on his rail car.
Mr. Schmidt had 50 pies cooked for him to take back to Washington with him.
Well, when it came time to build the Duncan area, they didn't have the money.
So Elliot Roosevelt was on the board of directors.
So he gets in touch with his dad to get a loan.
Well, the story is, the great influence were those pies.
And that each pie was worth $40,000.
It came out, 50 pies, $40,000 to build the entire Duncan area.
And to further about that story, and this may be partially hearsay, was that really it was,
Elliot's mother who got interested in the lawn and really was the power behind it.
You mean Elliot?
You mean Eleanor Roosevelt?
Yeah, Eleanor.
And the money then was loaned, I think, by Jesse Jones.
And one of the reasons that I found it a little bit amusing, we were still paying on Duncan when I came back here.
in 1965, and I don't know when it was paid off, but we were still paying on Duncan.
Because it is a bond.
All right, Duncan is a new facility when you arrive as a student?
Yes, it finished in 39.
I got here in 40.
And Hotard said the first year he operated that he was afraid to go out among the students because all the equipment he had was just to boil
You had to boil the meat, boil the vegetables, boil everything.
He said he couldn't fry or couldn't bake anything.
So he said, I didn't even go out among where anybody could see me.
But that became the $40,000 pie, and that story's in that book.
All right, who are some other celebrities that you remember serving
in the 20 years plus?
Oh, Governor Connolly was here, lots of the governors, and they just came here routinely.
And before my time, one of the people at the Sabisa that was there said Clarence Darrow had eaten in the Sabisa.
And the Prince of Saudi Arabia was dying there.
But the governors was about as high as we ever had, to my knowledge.
Now, after they built the new facilities, they began to have some dignitaries, a couple of presidents and those people there, but not in the dining halls.
They never came down to that place.
They'd be serving.
You were looking at your notes for some other items.
Oh, well, let's see.
We covered nearly everything.
We got $1.50 a day.
That was what you...
Oh, at early on?
Yes, and it was hard to break out of that.
That was the cost of the food and beverage?
For the day.
For the day?
For each person.
When you left, when you retired, reckon what that figure was?
Oh, it was not, not, it was about double that, about double that.
And we had a, we had a big menu.
That was for one entree, of course, and two vegetables, and dessert and beverage.
And Sebesa alone had 28 entrees, which might have been too elaborate, I don't know, but now they keep adding to it.
In your years, did the cost of supplying food for students, were the costs higher in Duncan or Sebesa, or were they about the same?
Maybe a little higher in Duncan, particularly at times.
The food cost in the university always runs high.
For male students, it always runs a little higher than that.
And for places restricted.
Of course, the missed meal factor is the only way we survive.
That's the only way we survive.
And that was true when I was a student.
Of course, when I was a student, everybody ate every meal except on the weekend.
Everybody tried to leave on the weekend.
Well, it had changed.
When I got here, they missed a lot of meals, but they had a little more money.
They could eat outside, and they skipped other meals.
I finally got it reduced to 20 meals a week because it was just too intense in some ways.
And so, it's been that way since.
Uh, it's, it's, it's interesting.
I, I don't know whether I'd do it if I had to do it or not.

I told somebody once, I thought I'd decorate flowers, uh, and decorate with flowers instead, because you could work for hundreds of hours at Escalona Buffet, and the most elaborate thing you've ever seen was special setups.
And about 30 minutes before the, the, the, the, oh, you open the doors, here comes the florist dancing in and puts a few flowers together.
The first person that walks through there says, what beautiful flowers.
When you all had worked days off.
Except for Governor Clements.
He saw the food.
Did he?
That's true.
Most of them did, really.
Let's see.
Did we finish a while ago on advice to the A&M leadership today that you might have?
Well, maybe we didn't.

I would hope that they would give good support to the Department of Field Services and give them liberty to operate so that they could operate in a manner in which they knew would respond to the desires of their customer, which is a student, which is always a little removed from administration, further removed than it is from the people within the operations.
And that's about the only thing I would want them to do.
But the main thing is to guard against the going outside to seek the commercialization of their operation when they can get good people within their own establishment.
Let's see.
whether it involved you directly or not, what's your favorite Aggie funny story, amusing story?
I don't know that I have one.
I never gave that any thought.
I guess it's the fact that...
What you call an Aggie five years after graduation is lost.
If I had been down, I never gave that much thought.
All right.
Then I guess just about the last one would be let's make believe that someone comes in and gives you a big cash gift and says, I want you to, I'm talking about big money,
And I want you to give it to whatever it is at A&M that you care most about, that you would most want to help.
What would that, where, to whom would, or to what area or areas would you give it?
For what purpose?
Well, if it's enough money, I'd say to start a school on food management.
Because I tried to get that done for many years.
I wrote the first letter on it in 1966.
Right.
And President Rudder, with appropriate clarification, Howard and others, and asking that we get something going.
And nothing happened, so Dr. Potts found out about it and said, let me take over that.
And he tried as hard as anybody could to do that.
But every time we'd get in gear for it, they'd say, well, this is not the time for that.
And this went on for years.
In the meantime, all these other schools went ahead and did it.
And what happens, the fact that we don't have that means that we have all this technical training, and we have down here all this ag science training.
But right here in the middle is a hole.
And that hole is made up of food management.
It could easily be incorporated within things we already have, like merchandising and
It's a fairly large national industry.
It is the largest employer, one of the three or four largest employers consistently within each state and within the nation.
And I've had people come to me and say, well, you know, we've already trained dieticians.
I say, yes, but the top food management hires dieticians.
And that's good, but dietetics is part of it.
So we have never had that, and probably never will.
For some reason, the people within an institution like this that are scientifically inclined particularly feel that it's just a little beneath the dignity.
There's not enough science in it.
I said, well, I've told most of those people that I've heard, I said, well, there's both science and art.
It combines everything.
And I'd always hoped, but I would still try that.
I was offered, Mr. Sabiza's grandson once came up, and we were in a down period, and he heard about our efforts.
He didn't have a lot of money, but he had
He said, I've got $25,000 I want to give you for this school.
At the time, I said, there's no use.
It's on the bottom of the barrel.
And we'll have to wait for better times.
That was a Mr. Kerr.
And he had told me a lot about his dad.
And granddad, he was.
He died in Cuba.
I didn't know that.
Well, she's buried out there.
Yeah.
But they died in Cuba.
Was he on vacation?
No, no, his son.
Oh, I see, I see.
Because he was Austrian, wasn't he?
Yes, yes, he was Austrian.
They had to give him some gold to come over here.
That's right.
He had storms, and a firefighter ran him out of Galveston.
He was a very ingenious individual.
That's what I heard.
Ingenious person.
And so was Hotar.
And Duffy might have been.
I didn't know.
I didn't know much about country, but I know that Seville and Oak Grove are outstanding in many respects.
Well, you carried on in a splendid fashion in your tradition.
I got by.
And I'm grateful to you for all that you've meant to this university, and I thank you for your time today.
If I've been anything, I'm grateful.
Oh, thank you.
